This is determined through the narrating role women play as biological mothers. These embedded understandings of mothering are significant in understanding paternal responsibility in Antigua and Barbuda, for even though men may reduce or claim paternity out of court, men’s gender role of provisioning and offering security prevails over the opposite gendered action of being cautious.
Although a man’s power is attributed to economic resources, men are also expected to be firm and decisive. For example, men associate the “daddy image” to their role as care giver, protector, and decision maker. During community focus group discussions, fathers discuss things that “good” fathers do. Those who stray from this ideal often end up being labeled as children’s parents, which tends to be viewed negatively. Even within the community organizations, the physical and mental health administrator suggests that a majority of mothers blame fathers for making them pregnant. However, these same mothers do not mind receiving their share of assistance from the fathers of their children, which suggests that the children’s mother is considered the only “real” parent, whereas the father is only temporarily present.
